The article highlights the increased risk of child abuse and neglect due to the COVID-19 pandemic and economic crisis. Children and families of color are particularly affected. Community-based child abuse prevention programs are crucial in supporting families and reducing the likelihood of abuse. The article acknowledges the efforts of frontline workers and calls for expanding prevention initiatives and addressing sexual violence against children and adolescents. It also promotes National Child Abuse Prevention Month as an opportunity to raise awareness and take action to protect children and support families.